annotations:
Tie a lasso ’round the Moon
 And bring it on down to you
Bailey alludes to George Bailey’s ‘You want the moon? I’ll tie a lasso around it and pull it down for you" speech from the 1946 cult classic movie 'It’s a Wonderful Life’.

I’d give you the Sun if you asked me
 You could have all of the time
 You could have the stars and the trees
 When dividing up the Universe
This is very likely to be referencing the book, “I’ll Give You the Sun” which is about two siblings who, have a game in which they divide the universe amongst themselves.
Darling, I’d wait for you

The affectionate noun “darling” is used to express the fondness between the two personas. The speaker would “wait” for their person, which has connotations that they are special to the speaker and the pronoun “you” emphasises this.

An acoustic snippet of the song was first posted to Bailey’s TikTok account on October 18, 2020, garnering over 1.2M views and 400,000 likes.

https://www.tiktok.com/@dasdelaney/video/6884734067007311109?lang=en&is_copy_url=0&is_from_webapp=v2&sender_device=pc&sender_web_id=6900167876305962502

annotations:
You said you hated blondes, so I bleached my hair dead
 ’Cause I loved to think that seeing my hair would make you see red
She likes think that she has power over the other person and their emotions so she thinks that since they hate blondes seeing her, now that she’s blonde, will make them mad
I don’t care anymore

Finally, the speaker has arrived at the present tense when describing her feelings towards this other person. It took her the whole song, but she’s able to realize that she shouldn’t care this much about what reminds her of this other person, who played with her feelings and let her down. The idea that this is a change in mentality is reaffirmed by her repetition of the future tense of this line, and the slight pause between her final declaration.

Baby, I want my requited love
 Without you, I’ll be just fine

This identifies a turning point in not only the speakers tone, but also their mentality surrounding their relationship with the other person. Coming to terms with the idea that she deserves the requited love and attention that she wants, she starts to tell herself that she will, in fact, be fine without this person who manipulated her feelings so.

I stopped asking questions ’cause I never thought I heard the truth
 Turns out the truth hurts less than the lies

An interpretation of the story the speaker aims to confront in this song, is that she was involved in a relationship where she was being led, constantly looking for validation and being lured by the other person for it. It seems that she must’ve stopped asking questions about the other person’s preferences, or likes/dislikes in general, because she thought they were lying about all of them matching up with her own personality. Later, she finds out that it was all a lie or a game to lead her on, and that hurts much more than them just lying about what they prefer.

I won’t care, I won’t care
 I won’t care, I won’t care
 I won’t care, I won’t care anymore

The repetition of this statement in the pleading tone the speaker uses, resembles someone convincing themself to follow through with something that is difficult to do. She’s clearly convincing herself to do all this, ironically, just for the sake of losing the memory and attention of this anonymous lover. She hasn’t accepted it yet, and is pleading with herself that it will work eventually.

And what’s it really matter anyway, it’s just hair
 It grows back again and by then you’ll move on

An interesting aspect of this lyric is that the speaker seems to be echoing these statements that we usually see as self reassurances, when confronting a situation where you’re convincing yourself to accept something. In this case, the speaker is aiming to confront the fact that she no longer needs to validate and appeal to this other person’s preferences, because later, they’ll have moved on. And so will she.

I started drinking coffee, so my teeth aren’t perfectly white
 ’Cause you used to say that you liked white teeth, right?

Throughout the song, the speaker describes factors of her life that were subject to appreciation by this anonymous admirer, and how she goes to lengths to get rid of them- since they liked white teeth, she stained her own. Since they hated blonde hair, she bleached her own in order to kill it, paint it blonde.
 Whether the relationship was just a failed one or a love unrequited, the irony of the situation is the speaker going to all these lengths in order to dispel all traces of this person she claims she doesn’t care at all about.

annotations:
Shove a sock down my throat again
 Remind me I’m not funny again

In an abusive relationship, people will often become accustomed to that pain, and feel comfortable in it. After breaking up, Delaney almost misses the pain their ex brought because without it, she feels unworthy
For you
The overall idea of this song is that she feels like she is too much.
And I’ll ask how are things for you

Going back to earlier in the song, she apologizes for oversharing, but here she expects them to talk about themselves to bring the attention off of her. This line is about giving more than you take, and this idea of a one-sided friendship being the only place where she feels that she isn’t taking up too much space.
I’ll hide my tail between my legs

This is in reference to how a dog behaves when it submits. They make themselves smaller to show that they are not a threat. She is doing the same thing by hiding these pieces of herself to conform (or submit) to who others want her to be.
So that I can fit in the palms of your hands
So that she can take up less space
Need to make myself small again
She needs to get rid of her big personality.
But pardon me, I’ve overshared
She feels that she has unloaded her problems onto this person, making her harder to love. These things need to be held in to not burden anyone.
So that I can be loved again
To be loved she needs to be what other people want her to be.

I’m getting too
 Comfortable in my skin again
 Laughing too loudly at my own jokes again

This line imitates the feeling of being out and enjoying yourself and suddenly realizing you don’t want to be there anymore.

You feel as though you are taking up too much space, emotionally and physically.
